Hey @purge - welcome 👋 

Criteria is laid out in the code for each task, with the core tasks being: 
- Q&A - <https://github.com/RogueTensor/bitagent_subnet/blob/main/bitagent/task_api/criteria/qna_criteria.py>
- Tool Calling - <https://github.com/RogueTensor/bitagent_subnet/blob/main/bitagent/task_api/criteria/tool_call_criteria.py>
- Vision - <https://github.com/RogueTensor/bitagent_subnet/blob/main/bitagent/task_api/criteria/qna_plot_criteria.py>

As for the model that validators and the task api use - <https://github.com/RogueTensor/bitagent_subnet/tree/main?tab=readme-ov-file#running-locally>
They use Mistral 7B instruct - but just know this model is not necessarily all you'll need.
Most of the effort is in designing the pipeline:
- Q&A requires passing back citations and implementing RAG - the validator knows the answer for citations and will compare your response to mistral's
- Tool Calling requires using a model that supports function calling or at least can follow instruction to return JSON through prompting, you may need to add in guided decoding or find or build a good fine tune - the validator knows the right tool and params so will grade you on that and compare the assistance response to mistral, but does not run a model to compare the tool selection against
- Vision works pretty well with the phi model - but again the validator knows the answer, so similar to tool call, there isn't a validator model that you're comparing to in this case

HTH

# 🚀 SN20 Tool Calling Fine Tune Subnet - BitAgent :onfire: 

## 📢  What's up? :yipee: 
We've got some pretty big news ... SN20 / BitAgent is tightening focus.
Over the last many months, we've investigated incentive mechanisms in Summation, RAG, Vision, Tool Generation and primarily Tool Calling. 
SN20 is committed to improving open source agency and will focus solely on Tool Calling going forward.
As such, we'll be evaluating miners on their weekly Hugging Face (HF) model submissions / fine tunes for Tool Calling.

## 🗒️ Task Changes:
- Focused only on Tool Calling
- No more: QnA/citations, Tool Gen, Conversation, etc., just Tool Calling

## 🔍 Validation Changes:
- Task API is going away - it had a good run 🫡 
- Validators will need at a minimum 48GB of VRAM, but may run out of memory with batching during offline evaluation, it's recommended to have 80GB of VRAM
- Validators will run a 7B model for task generation and an ~8B parameter model for each miner's HF submission

- Will continue to run tool calling capability that is on par or better than the TOP miner's HF submission
- Additionally, will now push a trained or fine-tuned 8B parameter tool calling model to a shared HF repo and release under Apache 2.0 for the community to use

## 💯  Incentive Mechanism: 
Tasking will be in 2 parts:
- HF Fine Tune submission Evaluation - miners' HF model submissions are queried for evaluation (all offline)
  - evaluation against the Berkeley Function Calling tasks
  - evaluation against the Glaive Function Calling tasks
  - evaluation against the BitAgent Function Calling tasks
  - worth 50%
- Tool Calling Task query evaluation - miners are queried to complete tasks for evaluation
  - must respond to validator queries and respond with a similar response to the subnet's TOP HF model
  - worth 50%

- Task API (while it exists) has been set to ONLY query for tool calling

We are pleased to announce a series of significant updates to the subnet, aimed at improving inference structure, evaluation criteria, and dataset consistency. These changes will enhance overall reliability, reduce miner infrastructure costs, and improve validator consensus.

### **Inference Format Structure Update**  
- Task inference has transitioned from our proprietary tool-type to a more standard JSON format.

- The first new dataset segment has been uploaded, consisting of 1,000 tasks blended from previous datasets. Each segment will be targeting specific areas of miner performance
- This curated set will rotate periodically in 3-7 day intervals, promoting validator alignment and discouraging miner overfitting.

Digging deeper into the datagen code, now I believe that there are only 111 example in the dataset, and not 333.

The task generation process creates only 111 unique tasks despite having 333 dataset items. Each unique task appears exactly 3 times at regular intervals (indices 0, 111, 222).
Pattern:
```Task 0   → Dataset item 0 (for positive) + items 1,2 (for negative)
Task 1   → Dataset item 3 (for positive) + items 4,5 (for negative)
...
Task 111 → Dataset item 0 (for positive) + items 1,2 (for negative) [repeat]
Task 222 → Dataset item 0 (for positive) + items 1,2 (for negative) [repeat again]```
Cause:
* Fixed random seed creates deterministic behaviour
* Dataset cycles through all 333 items sequentially
* Each task accesses exactly 3 items: one for the positive tool and exactly two for negative tools (because the seed is fixed and tool dataset is initialized at every iteration, it will be exactly two times every time, despite `random.randint(2,4)` )
* After 111 tasks (333 items), the pattern repeats from the beginning
